<paragraph id="186B325E06147402AC74886524B61320" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
(
<emphasis id="0538AD129B3834AAC35584FFC4EB9041" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">N</emphasis>
= 124): H 1.6-2.1 mm, B 1.3-1.7 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="55830C3AD298EBCBBB11935686A14D5B" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="285E4BE4D200F85A496EFF6837D35A44" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AF6381652C629CACEF4461FD6086246B" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8F9B0677AA30BEACA0F98899CA02A6D1" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 12. Type locality of E. wangchuki; Bhutan, district Wangdue Phodrang, Gangchhu, Gangzetem brooklet, 2883 m a. s. l. Photo by A. C. Gittenberger-de Groot." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402719" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">12</figureCitation>
). See 
<bibRefCitation id="9FDE48FFEB6059787706B3DA5BB96437" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.679.13326" author="Gittenberger, E" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" pagination="21 - 28" refId="B7" refString="Gittenberger, E, Sherub, S, Stelbrink, B, 2017a. Erhaia Davis &amp; Kuo (Gastropoda, Rissooidea, Amnicolidae) also in Bhutan. ZooKeys 679: 21 - 28, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.679.13326" title="Erhaia Davis &amp; Kuo (Gastropoda, Rissooidea, Amnicolidae) also in Bhutan." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.679.13326" volume="679" year="2017 a">Gittenberger et al. (2017a)</bibRefCitation>
for data about the Gangzetem brooklet and its surroundings. The snails are very common on the pebbles and rocks in the open area near the road, next to the water powered prayer wheel.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6C064F1B7DEF0485C75245158B418D99" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="dna data">
<paragraph id="D15F8375D2DFB26B897F7C4E2009195B" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">DNA data</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5E112A0DF2FC0FFC519337CDB6BDF9CD" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DA7AF1E5F404BA477D7ABEF0436F13DA" captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 18. Maximum likelihood tree reconstructed with RAxML BlackBox (Stamatakis et al. 2008; GTR + G substitution model for each partition and 100 bootstrap replicates) based on the 16 S rRNA and COI dataset of Liu et al. (2014) and Guan et al. (2008), with new data in red. Numbers on branches denote bootstrap values&gt; 50." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/402724" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">18</figureCitation>
). A single individual (GenBank acc. nos. KY798003 and MT237715, for 16S rRNA and COI, respectively) is genetically distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="3407168EDEFD8610AFB7611EBFADAAA4" genus="E." lsidName="E. jannei" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" rank="species" species="jannei">
<emphasis id="88C27445F5DDD8A86B5A81FDCD0D111C" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">E. jannei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see data for that species) and showed genetic distances of 2.74% for 16S rRNA and 11.43% for COI compared to 
<taxonomicName id="2E00FAC08423A9BA9C4468DB70254F36" authorityName="Davis &amp; Kuo" authorityYear="1985" class="Gastropoda" family="Amnicolidae" genus="Erhaia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erhaia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D0DFBE5569B4E83E5E4FA5506BFE58EC" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Erhaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. from China, Guangxi (GenBank acc. nos. KC832722 and KC832701).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CAAEDA5F46297D99A81C7E02A4DCEE1C" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="notes">
<paragraph id="82F929D67F989817CBD37FC6E7D84E85" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="86A06058BAF7B75860A9B9EB985528E5" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Only three relatively large shells form the type series of this species. Many more specimens, none of which exceed 1.7 mm in breadth and over 2.0 mm in height, were collected recently. This necessitated some adaptations in the description of the shells. Contrary to the original description, the shell should be described as higher than broad.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4CF8BA389C3BAD94BFBEEB38F5FEAE46" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="erhaia in nepal and northern india">
<paragraph id="C2238C5DD0075DD916E190DE0A1793CA" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName id="AAAE771725A600296BE358FD743FEA07" authorityName="Davis &amp; Kuo" authorityYear="1985" class="Gastropoda" family="Amnicolidae" genus="Erhaia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erhaia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
